@Lucien Liu 
Hey Lucien, 
you made such an interesting point regarding factors like atmospheric circulation and ocean currents contributing to more or less dorught like factors. This is very interesting to evaluate, especially since Florida, my community, is largely affected by high ocean currents that bring in winds, leading in cooler temperatures and very rarely, drought. I wonder how oceanic wind patterns compare for the east and west coast, even in Florida!

@Reid Giribaldi 

Hey Reid! 
First of all, I think you make some very good points about the issue of drought being widespread and I also greatly respect your concern for the problem and how we would be able to potentially solve it. Additionally, I think it is very interesting that you brought up the term “Landlocked” which was a term i had never heard of before and actually helped to answer one of my own questions in addition to exposing me to new vocabulary. Furthermore, in regards to your question on what could be done about the current state of drought in the US, I believe the best place to start would be to focus on how climate change and global warming are worsening the problem and as such, tackle the primary initiator of those issues so that we may gain a better understanding of how the problem is worsening and chipping away at small pieces at a time.

@Jasneet 

Hey Jasneet!

Youve made some great observations that I myself nearly overlooked! And I have to agree, I believe that it is really interesting to think about the possibilities of climate change and effects of droughts on the country and how it can lead to potential survivability issues. I myself believe that the united states would probably go into a short state of “shock” if the shift in droughts is very sudden as states such as florida and colorado would not be initially very prepared to handle the shift in conditions, however, I also believe that the country would very quickly adapt to these changes in climate. Additionally it could bring with it more of a demand for things such as water and produce potentially leading to either significant inflation or deflation of prices for those goods.

